During the last ten years we have learned that if we are to get to the truth about mediaeval gilds, we must abendon many currently accepted opinions, aud commence the work of detailed research once more. We cannot classify gilds satisfactorily, until we know how lar the same gild preserved the same character throughout its whole history, or whether it took on new functione to meet the requireurents of a new era. We do not · understand the mutual relations of the gilds in any one place unless we can say how far particular gilds were exclusive, and how far they included the members of other gilds3 this we can only determine by an examination of the lists of members¹.
